[[File:Beddenpan-bovenzijde.jpg|thumb|Bed warmer from The Netherlands]]
[[File:Electrical Bed Heater, Dharamkot.jpg|thumb|Electrical bed warmer (with a shielded electric bulb) in [[Dharamkot (Himachal Pradesh)]], India, 1979]]

A '''bed warmer'''  was a common household item in countries with cold [[winter]]s, especially in [[Europe]].{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}  It consisted of a [[metal]] container, usually fitted with a handle and shaped somewhat like a modern [[frying pan]], with a solid or finely perforated lid.  The pan would be filled with river stones preheated from the fireplace and placed under the [[bed sheet|cover]]s of a [[bed]], to warm it up and/or dry it out before use.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} 

After the invention of [[rubber]], the classical bed warmer was largely supplanted by the [[hot water bottle]], which is still widely used.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}}  In the early<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=VygDAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA62&as_pt=MAGAZINES&pg=PA62#v=onepage&q=&f=false]</ref> 20th century, [[electric blanket]]s and then the [[electric bed warmer]], (containing a lampholder and low wattage light bulb), were invented to fulfill the same need.

