{{Infobox aircraft occurrence |name = Cubana de Aviación Flight 9646 |occurrence_type = Accident |image = Cubana Il-62M CU-T1208 SXF 1990-8-18.png |image_size = 250 |alt = |caption = A Cubana [[Il-62M]] similar to the one involved in the accident is seen here at [[Berlin Schönefeld Airport]] in 1990. |date = 3 September 1989 |type = [[Pilot error]]<ref name="FI1989-17"/> |site = [[Havana]], Cuba |coordinates = <!--These 17 entries for single-aircraft occurrence:------> |aircraft_type = [[Ilyushin Il-62M]] |aircraft_name = |operator = [[Cubana de Aviación|Cubana]] |tail_number = CU-T1281 |origin = [[José Martí International Airport]] |stopover = [[Malpensa Airport]] |stopover0 = |stopover1 = |stopover2 = |stopover3 = |last_stopover = |destination = [[Cologne Bonn Airport]] |passengers = 115 |crew = 11 |injuries = |total_fatalities = 150 |ground_fatalities = 24 |occupants = 126 |survivors = 0 }} '''Cubana de Aviación Flight 9646''' was a chartered [[Ilyushin Il-62M]] airliner, ([[Aircraft registration|registered]] CU-T1281) operated by [[Cubana de Aviación|Cubana]], that crashed on 3 September 1989, shortly after [[takeoff]] from [[José Martí International Airport]].<ref name="ASN"/>
Flight 9646 was due to operate a non-scheduled international [[Havana]]–[[Milan]]–[[Cologne]] passenger service. The crash resulted in the deaths of all 126 occupants of the aircraft plus 24 people on the ground.{{#tag:ref|According to ''Aviation Safety Network''.<ref name="ASN"/> Another source informed the number of ground casualties to be 14.<ref name="FI1990"/>|group="nb"}}
==Accident== The aircraft took off in heavy rain and wind gusts of {{convert|30|-|50|mph}}.<ref name="ASN"/><ref name="FI1989-4"/> The [[Aircrew|crew]] retracted the flaps from their initial 30° position to 15°, in an attempt to gain speed, but this action reduced the ability of the aircraft to provide [[Lift (force)|lift]].<ref name="FI1989-17"/> The plane climbed to about {{convert|53|m}}, where it was hit by a downdraft that caused the airframe to strike the end of the runway, subsequently hitting a navigational facility and a small hill before crashing into a residential area, about one minute after takeoff.<ref name="FI1989-17"/><ref name="ASN"/><ref name="FI1989-4"/> All 126 people on board—115 passengers, most of them Italian holidaymakers, and a crew of 11<ref name="FI1989-4"/><ref name="Jet With 54 on Board Missing in Brazil : Disappears Over Amazon; Toll in Cuban Crash May Reach 150" />—perished in the accident. An additional 24 people, who were not aboard the aircraft also lost their lives as a result of the accident.<ref name="ASN"/>
==Cause== Investigators attributed the crash of Flight 9646 to the pilot's decision to fly after an abrupt deterioration in the meteorological conditions. The pilot underestimated the risks of taking off and misjudged the aircraft's performance in poor weather.<ref name="Gero">{{cite book |title=Aviation Disasters Second Edition |last1=Gero |first1=David |publisher=Patrick Stephens Limited |year= 1996 |page=212 }}</ref>
==Aftermath== {{As of|2018|05}}, the accident remains the deadliest aviation mishap to occur on [[Cuba|Cuban soil]], followed by [[Cubana de Aviación Flight 972]].<ref name="The Sun">{{cite web|last1=Knox|first1=Patrick|title=JET FIREBALL Cuba plane crash – ‘110 killed as three survivors pulled from wreckage’ in Havana as Boeing 737 explodes moments after takeoff|url=https://www.thesun.co.uk/news/6322724/cuba-plane-crash-latest-havana-boeing-737-airliner-latest-marti-international-airport/|website=The Sun|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title= Accident record for Cuba|url= http://aviation-safety.net/database/dblist.php?Country=CU|publisher= Aviation Safety Network|accessdate= 3 October 2013}}</ref>
