'''Dansk Ornitologisk Forening''' (DOF), also known as the '''Danish Ornithological Society''' or '''BirdLife Denmark''', is a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[Non-governmental organization|non-governmental]] [[Nonprofit organization|non-profit organisation]].  Founded on 15 October 1906 by Eiler Lehn Schiøler and [[Hans Christian Cornelius Mortensen]], it is the principal [[ornithology|bird study]] and [[bird conservation|conservation]] organisation in the country and the Danish partner of [[BirdLife International]].  It has about 12,000 members in 12 local branches and administers 18 bird reserves.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dofbasen.dk/english/ |title=A brief introduction to DOFbasen |accessdate=2012-11-26 |work=DOFbasen |first= |last= |publisher= Dansk Ornitologisk Forening |date= }}</ref>  It publishes the journal ''Dansk Ornitologisk Forenings Tidsskrift'' (Journal of the Danish Ornithological Society) and the magazine ''Fugle og Natur'' (Birds and Nature).  DOF was responsible for establishing the network of volunteer caretaker groups that watch over Denmark’s 128 [[Important Bird Area]]s, and in the designation of [[Special Protection Area]]s which have legal protection under the [[European Union]].<ref>{{cite web|work=birdlife.org |year=2011|title= In Denmark, voluntary ‘Caretaker’ groups have been instrumental in the designation of SPAs. Presented as part of the BirdLife State of the world's birds website|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/sowb/casestudy/434|accessdate=November 26, 2012}}</ref>

