{{Infobox power station | name = Neuhardenberg Solar Park | name_official = | image = | image_size = | image_caption = | image_alt = | location_map = Brandenburg | location_map_size = | location_map_caption = Location of Neuhardenberg Solar Park in Brandenburg | coordinates = {{coord|52|36|50|N|14|14|33|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | coordinates_ref = | country = Germany | location = [[Neuhardenberg]] | status = O | construction_began = | commissioned = 30 September 2012 | decommissioned = | cost = EUR 280 million (USD 365 million)<ref>[http://www.solarserver.com/solar-magazine/solar-news/current/2011/kw50/solarhybrid-receives-lease-permitting-approval-for-150-mw-pv-plant-at-former-military-airport-in-brandenburg-germany.html Solarhybrid receives lease, permitting approval for 150 MW PV plant at former military airport in Brandenburg, Germany]</ref> | owner = Solarhybrid | operator = | solar_type = pv | ps_units_operational = 600,000 | solar_cpv_concentration = | solar_site_area = 240 ha<ref>[https://www.panoramio.com/photo/79135566 Hier entsteht Deutschlands größter Solarpark - Here shall built Germany's largest solar park]</ref> | ps_electrical_capacity = 145 [[Megawatt|MW]] | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | website = | extra = }}
'''Neuhardenberg Solar Park''' is a 145-[[megawatt]] (MW) [[photovoltaic power plant]], and was Europe's largest [[solar power]] station, located at the former [[Neuhardenberg]] military airport in Brandenburg, Germany.<ref>[http://oekonews.at/index.php?mdoc_id=1074015 Solarpark "Neuhardenberg" in Brandenburg eröffnet] (German)</ref>
In 2015 a [[solar battery]] storage facility with a rated power of 5 MW and 5 MWh capacity was added, which was commissioned in mid 2016.<ref>[http://www.pv-magazine.de/nachrichten/details/beitrag/grospeicher-in-brandenburg-nimmt-regelbetrieb-auf_100023688/ ''Großspeicher in Brandenburg nimmt Regelbetrieb auf'']. In: ''[[PV-Magazine]]'', 6th July 2016. Retrieved 8th Juli 2016. (German)</ref>
