'''SymbioCity''' is the [[trademark]]ed term for [[Sweden]]'s approach to sustainable [[urban development]].<ref name="urbantrekker"/> Established in 2008, the program's primary goal is to export Sweden's knowledge and experience with sustainable cities.<ref name="MIPIM 2010">{{cite conference | title = Swedes manage urban growth | page = 10 | booktitle = MIPIM News | date = 18 March 2010 | volume = 3 | editor-last = Strohm | editor-first = Paul | conference = MIPIM 2010 | conferenceurl = http://www.mipim.com/en/mipim/why-mipim/highlights-from-mipim-2010/ | publisher = Reed MIDEM | location = Paris | url = http://pvevent1.immanens.com/en/pvPage2.asp?skin=mim&pa=1&puc=002304&nu=3 | accessdate = 2010-09-14}}</ref> It was created in order to assist Swedish environmental technology companies with their international marketing by creating a common trademark.
[[Gunnar Lund]], Swedish ambassador to [[France]], said in 2010, "The starting point for SymbioCity is the predicted growth of our population from six billion to nine billion in the next two decades".<ref name="MIPIM 2010"/>
SymbioCity aims to "get more for less", creating [[synergy]] by integrating different technologies and city functions.<ref name=urbantrekker>{{cite web |url=http://www.metrodcliving.com/urbantrekker/2008/03/symbiocity-sust.html |title=SymbioCity Sustainable Urban Development |work=Urban Trekker |accessdate=2010-07-16}}</ref> For example, waste can turn into energy, waste water can turn into fuel, and the excessive heat from an industry can warm up a household. According to the SymbioCity approach, environmental and economic gains result from unlocking synergies between urban systems. The seven building blocks of SymbioCity are: [[Architecture]]; [[Energy]]; [[Landscape planning|Landscape Planning]]; Traffic & Transport; [[Waste Management]]; Urban Functions, Industry and Buildings; Water Supply and Sanitation. Several hundred Swedish consultants, contractors and system suppliers are connected to SymbioCity.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://symbiocity.org/?pageId=2 |title=SymbioCity Sustainability by Sweden |publisher=SymbioCity |accessdate=2010-07-16}}</ref> SymbioCity is scalable, and adaptable to any climate.<ref name="urbantrekker"/>
SymbioCity as a trademark was launched in 2008,<ref>{{cite press release | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/pressRelease/idUS243375+28-Feb-2008+PRN20080228 | title=Maud Olofsson, Deputy Prime Minister, Will Unveil Sweden's 'SymbioCity' at WIREC 2008 in Washington D.C. | date=2008-02-28 | publisher = Swedish Trade Council }}</ref> and is administered by the [[Swedish Trade Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.swedishtrade.se/miljoteknik/?objectid=6390&pageid=6864 | title = Export av hållbar stadsutveckling, miljö- & energiteknik |trans-title=Exports of sustainable urban development, Environment & Energy | publisher=Swedish Trade Council | location = Stockholm | accessdate = 2010-07-16 }}</ref> The name SymbioCity is a play on words, combining "[[symbiosis]]" and "city".{{Citation needed|date=July 2010}}
The 2008 [[Environmental Performance Index]] ranks Sweden third in the world.<ref name=urbantrekker/>
